  "notes": [
    "PREPARATION FOR THE MINOR One of the following calculus sequences: AM 11A: Mathematical Methods for Economists I AND AM 11B: Mathematical Methods for Economists II MATH 11A: Calculus with Applications AND MATH 11B: Calculus with Applications MATH 19A: Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics AND MATH 19B: Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics Plus one course from each of the following four categories: Statistical Concepts: STAT 5: Statistics STAT 7: Statistical Methods for the Biological, Environmental, and Health Sciences AND STAT 7L: Statistical Methods for the Biological, Environmental, and Health Sciences STAT 17: Statistical Methods for Business and Economics AND STAT 17L: Statistical Methods for Business and Economics Laboratory Computer Programming: CSE 20: Beginning Programming in Python CSE 30: Programming Abstractions: Python Linear Algebra: AM 10: Mathematical Methods for Engineers I MATH 21: Linear Algebra Multivariate Calculus: MATH 22: Introduction to Calculus of Several Variables AM 30: Multivariate Calculus for Engineers MATH 23A: Vector Calculus AND MATH 23B: Vector Calculus Please visit the Baskin Engineering Undergraduate Experience website to learn more about this minor.",
    "UC Santa Cruz students may choose to complete one or more minors, provided they can finish all required coursework within their maximum enrollment terms and allowable credits. While a minor will appear on a student's official transcript, it will not be listed on their diploma. Pursuing a minor is a personal decision that should align with a student's educational and career goals. Students do not apply for minors when submitting their application to UC Santa Cruz. After enrolling, transfer students interested in pursuing a minor should contact the department offering the minor for guidance."
